*GA:* I just think it appeals to a general news consumer that, =E2=80=9COh =
my gosh, Huawei could compete with Apple? Oh, no.=E2=80=9D The actual natio=
nal security people do not care at all about the Huawei smartphone. They ca=
re about the chip inside, what it suggests about China=E2=80=99s current se=
miconductor manufacturing ecosystem, and what that means about what Huawei =
could do with AI chips. Huawei has pretty clearly signaled, =E2=80=9CWe=E2=
=80=99re going to make AI chips. We=E2=80=99re going to make them at 7 nano=
meters.=E2=80=9D

Now how credible it is that they could do that and what timeframe depends o=
n a lot of unknown factors. How much capacity does SMIC, the chip fab that =
Huawei uses, have at 7 nanometers now? I think they have a credible path to=
 more than 20,000 wafers per month sometime next year at 7 nanometers, but =
if ASML is no longer selling them immersion DUV machines, then it=E2=80=99s=
 a lot harder to go past 20,000 wafers per month. Huawei needs 7 nanometer =
chips for a lot of stuff. It needs them for smartphones, it needs them for =
telecommunications infrastructure, it needs them for AI chips. That is one =
way in which the export controls can be useful even if they are imperfect. =
There is this capacity build out limitation that SMIC is very likely to enc=
ounter very soon.

*I think that is a super important point. It speaks to this idea that you c=
an only evaluate the effectiveness of these export controls =E2=80=94 again=
, leaving aside whether they=E2=80=99re good or not, if we=E2=80=99re just =
going to look at efficacy, it=E2=80=99s foolhardy to expect an impact in 20=
23, you have to look and think about the impact in 2030. I think we=E2=80=
=99re completely on the same page there.*

*The one thing that does occur to me, we didn=E2=80=99t mention this earlie=
r in terms of Nvidia, but I=E2=80=99m curious did this come up in conversat=
ions at all about this export ban, which is the advantage of selling the A8=
00 in China? It is limited as far as scalability because of that memory int=
erconnect issue we talked about. It also ensures that CUDA remains the domi=
nant framework. However, once Nvidia is completely cut out of China and you=
=E2=80=99re using these Ascend chips, which we=E2=80=99ll see about the rel=
ative performance in the long run, Huawei has, what, their CANN alternative=
 to CUDA ( https://blog.csdn.net/chengyq116/article/details/128292906 ). Ho=
wever, what I think what would make sense for China if they=E2=80=99re doin=
g this is something like what they=E2=80=99re doing with RISC-V, which is j=
ust open source in general. Open source is global, it=E2=80=99s not going t=
o be restricted to China, it=E2=80=99s arguable this is actually the bigges=
t longterm threat to CUDA and to Nvidia broadly not because they can=E2=80=
=99t sell to China, but because there is now a=E2=80=94*

*GA:* Captive market.

*Yeah, there=E2=80=99s a beachhead for an alternative ecosystem, and there=
=E2=80=99s no reason that ecosystem needs to be constrained to Nvidia. Reme=
mber every other US company would like to get out from under the thumb of N=
vidia if they could.*

*GA:* Right, and I think the Huawei CANN architecture is a competitor of CU=
DA, that=E2=80=99s explicitly how Huawei talks about it. They=E2=80=99re al=
so developing alternatives to the ML development framework. Huawei has Mind=
Spore ( https://e.huawei.com/kr/products/cloud-computing-dc/atlas/mindspore=
 ) , which is intended to be a competitor to PyTorch. They really are tryin=
g to vertically integrate from the machines that make chips all the way up =
to every aspect of the AI stack, CANN is explicitly aimed at breaking CUDA,=
 and now they have this captive market.

I thought it was really interesting that the person who announced this Huaw=
ei AI chip was not a Huawei executive, it was an iFlytek executive. iFlytek=
, which is best known as a speech recognition machine learning company, is =
really important in the AI surveillance state of China. Nvidia used to incl=
ude them in their presentations at the GTC conference, they used to be like=
, =E2=80=9CiFlytek is a great customer of Nvidia,=E2=80=9D until iFlytek fe=
ll under the entity listing and Nvidia wasn=E2=80=99t allowed to sell to th=
em anymore.

When Huawei goes to iFlytek, which is still a highly capable AI company in =
a lot of ways, iFlytek finds Huawei=E2=80=99s offerings very compelling bec=
ause they=E2=80=99re not legally allowed to acquire Nvidia. As the export c=
ontrols grow, what you call the beachhead or a captive market is also growi=
ng.

*I mean it=E2=80=99s interesting. You said something in there which actuall=
y I think is optimistic from the US perspective. It goes back to our Soviet=
 discussion we=E2=80=99ve had a couple of times, which is how Huawei wants =
to do the full stack. It=E2=80=99s like, =E2=80=9CGood luck with that.=E2=
=80=9D This idea that they=E2=80=99re going to have their own CUDA alternat=
ive instead of using Triton ( https://openai.com/research/triton ) and weav=
ing in PyTorch on top of that, whatever it might be, seems like a mistake. =
I suspect it=E2=80=99s one that they will make, because this is China and i=
t=E2=80=99s interesting. It=E2=80=99s weird also where this is arguably pro=
-competitive in the US, which is breaking Nvidia=E2=80=99s software-based h=
old on the market. Again, I mentioned that lots of US tech companies would =
like to see that happen and that=E2=80=99s certainly not going to happen if=
 it=E2=80=99s some Huawei proprietary thing. Leaning into existing framewor=
ks and alternatives would seem like a better strategy, which is just an int=
eresting second order effect of this new chip ban in particular.*

*GA:* You=E2=80=99re right. I think one difference about the Chinese market=
 versus say a Taiwan is that Taiwan can only reach relevant economies of sc=
ale through exporting. The Chinese domestic market is large enough that the=
y can reach relevant economies of scale and network effects just with their=
 domestic market, right? That=E2=80=99s why WeChat is interesting. That=E2=
=80=99s why Alibaba is interesting because even if you only or almost only =
serve the Chinese market, that=E2=80=99s still a colossal market. When Huaw=
ei thinks about CANN I think they=E2=80=99re envisioning, =E2=80=9CWe actua=
lly can get meaningful developer numbers using CANN. We can get meaningful =
adoption.=E2=80=9D Why they didn=E2=80=99t choose to go the route of OpenAI=
 Triton I think is a very legitimate question. CANN does I think predate Op=
enAI Triton.

*They could basically, there=E2=80=99s also OpenCL ( https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/OpenCL ) , which I think is basically get AMD on board=E2=80=94*

*GA:* Right, call AMD and be like, =E2=80=9CHello, we would love to help yo=
u.=E2=80=9D

*You don=E2=80=99t even need to do it explicitly, right? Microsoft and Meta=
 I think in particular have been super invested in trying to get AMD up to =
speed relative to Nvidia, which has been mostly a failure and it=E2=80=99s =
not just because of CUDA, there=E2=80=99s other issues at hand, but it is f=
ascinating and again I think call backs to the Soviet example where a pragm=
atic approach would probably help a lot here. We=E2=80=99ll see if it actua=
lly manifests, but, hey, enough advice for the Chinese.*

*Gregory Allen, it=E2=80=99s good to talk to you. I=E2=80=99m sure, as you =
mentioned, the rules will be updated yearly, we have at least a yearly appo=
intment. We=E2=80=99ll look forward to your report, which I will link when =
it comes out, but thanks for jumping online. I feel more knowledgeable abou=
t what just happened and I hope our listeners do as well.*

*GA:* Thanks for having me.

